@section Constructors


@defun char-set @var{char/range} ...
Build and return a new @code{char-set}.  The @var{char/range} arguments
may be the empty list or a mixed list of characters and ranges.
@end defun


@defun char-set-copy @var{cs}
Return a newly allocated @code{char-set} holding a copy of @var{cs}.
@end defun


@defun char-set-add @var{cs} @var{char/range}
Add values to an existing @var{char-set}.  @var{char/range} can be a
single character or a range.  Return a new instance of @code{char-set};
the returned set may share some structure with the arguments.
@end defun


@defun char-set-add! @var{cs} @var{char/range}
Add values to an existing @var{char-set}.  @var{char/range} can be a
single character or a range.  Return @var{cs} itself; the returned set
may share some structure with the arguments.
@end defun


@defvr Constant char-set-lower-bound
@defvrx Constant char-set-upper-bound
@defvrx Constant char-set-inner-upper-bound
@defvrx Constant char-set-inner-lower-bound
The character sets are defined by the Scheme standard to be in the
ranges @code{[0, #xD800)} and @code{(#xDFFF, #x10FFFF]}.
@library{vicare containers char-sets} exports these symbols, defined as follows:

@example
(define char-set-lower-bound
  (integer->char 0))

(define char-set-inner-upper-bound
  (integer->char (- #xD800 1)))

(define char-set-inner-lower-bound
  (integer->char (+ 1 #xDFFF)))

(define char-set-upper-bound
  (integer->char #x10FFFF))
@end example
@end defvr

