@section Predicates


@defun char-set? @var{obj}
Return @true{} if @var{obj} is a valid @code{char-set}, else return
@false{}.
@end defun


@defun char-set-empty? @var{cs}
Return @true{} if the @code{char-set} is empty, else return @false{}.
@end defun


@defun char-set-contains? @var{cs} @var{char}
Return @true{} if @var{char} is an element of @var{cs}.
@end defun


@defun char-set=? @var{cs-a} @var{cs-b}
Return @true{} if the arguments represent the same @code{char-set}, else
return @false{}.
@end defun


@defun char-set<? @var{cs-a} @var{cs-b}
Return @true{} if all the elements of @var{cs-a} are strictly less than
all the elements of @var{cs-b}, else return @false{}.  Empty sets cannot
be ordered, so if an argument is empty the return value is @false{}.
@end defun


@defun char-set-subset? @var{cs} ...
@defunx char-set-subset?/strict @var{cs} ...
Return @true{} if the arguments, in the given order, are subsets of each
other or strict subsets of each other, else return @false{}.  When
called with zero or one argument: return @true{}.
@end defun


@defun char-set-superset? @var{cs} ...
@defunx char-set-superset?/strict @var{cs} ...
Return @true{} if the arguments, in the given order, are supersets of
each other or strict supersets of each other, else return @false{}.
When called with zero or one argument: return @true{}.
@end defun

